      <hedline>
        <hl1>Witnesses in the Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Albert Z K Sanders letter, commenting on June 17 article on mass sex assault in Central Park, says it is disturbing that not one 911 call was made from all of the cell phones that must have been in the park that day</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In all the comment on the recent Central Park mass sexual assaults and the poor deployment and passivity of the police (front page, June 17), one crucial aspect has been underplayed: There must have been hundreds of cell phones available to the many spectators of the attacks.</p>
        <p>Did not even a single one of these citizens dial 911 and report a near riot with people being attacked? Didn't they have any sympathy or compassion or pity for the women being tormented and robbed? And are they such passive sheep that not one could take the least bit of initiative?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In all the comment on the recent Central Park mass sexual assaults and the poor deployment and passivity of the police (front page, June 17), one crucial aspect has been underplayed: There must have been hundreds of cell phones available to the many spectators of the attacks.</p>
        <p>Did not even a single one of these citizens dial 911 and report a near riot with people being attacked? Didn't they have any sympathy or compassion or pity for the women being tormented and robbed? And are they such passive sheep that not one could take the least bit of initiative?</p>
        <p>What does this say about how our schools teach civic responsibility? Or how our families and churches teach morality and sensitivity?</p>
        <p>ALBERT Z. K. SANDERS  New York, June 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
